body:
Matrix rewatch

Morpheus cheated.

He offered the blue pill in his left hand. Neo is left handed (watch him sign for his Nokia phone when sitting in his work cubicle) so he’ll reach with his left hand.

I’m not saying there’s no say in this but probability is he’ll go with what’s on his left.

Which is the red pill.

Well played, Mor-spying-on-you-for-2-years-pheus

body:
Little Rockstar (Theodore “Ted” Logan Imagine)

This was requested.

Summary: You’re attending a Wyld Stallyns concert and your son decides to rock out like his dad, Ted.

You and your four year old son, Ted Jr., were standing side stage at a Wyld Stallyns concert. Wyld Stallyns was a band that your husband and his best friend started together years ago. They had come a long way from playing in a garage. They had become legendary rockstars, selling out arenas across the country. They were doing a show for San Dimas, which was your hometown and were you still resided.

Ted Jr. was stood right by you while you were knelt down to his level. He was wearing his headphones so the loud music wouldn’t hurt his sensitive little ears. He clapped along to the music and was smiling really wide, proud of his daddy. You were also proud of your husband. He’d accomplished one of his biggest dreams and you couldn’t be happier for him.

“Daddy’s so good!” Ted Jr. yelled out as he looked at you.

You smiled and nodded as you looked at your son. He was the mini version of his father. His hair was dark and on the long side because he refused to wear it short. He also preferred to wear little band t-shirts. He was wearing a Wyld Stallyns one for the night with a pair of jeans and Converse. He was a cool little dude.

“He is good isn’t he?” You told him as you both looked back out on stage.

Ted just so happened to look your way when they finished the song. He waved at you both with a huge smile. You both waved back at him. Ted Jr. was a ball of energy just like his father and his uncle Bill so it was no surprise when he suddenly ran out on stage to join them. You facepalmed yourself and was about to run out and grab him, but Ted picked him up.

“Looks like little dude came out to rock with us,” Ted said into the microphone as everyone in the audience cooed at the little boy. He waved at everyone as he smiled real big. “San Dimas, this is my most excellent son, little Ted. Little Ted, say hello to everyone.”

“Hey, dudes!” Ted Jr. said to them all. “Be excellent to each other!”

The crowd cheered at that as you grinned real big. That kid was just like his father and it was the cutest thing ever. He took after you as well, but he definitely took after Ted. He was his hero and idol after all. Ted put little Ted back on his feet.

“Would you like to stay on stage for our last song, little dude?” Bill asked your son. “We’re playing your favorite.”

“Excellent!” Your son exclaimed as he did his very own air guitar move.

Everyone cheered again as you giggled at your little boy. Ted was looking down at him proudly before he looked back your way. You’d never seen your husband look so happy and proud. You blew him a kiss and he pretended to catch it before he started playing the next song. True to Bill’s word, it was Ted Jr.’s favorite song by them. He jumped around on stage and pretended he was playing his own imaginary guitar. Bill and Ted were rocking out with him while they played. Little Ted was singing the song with them and soaking up the crowds cheering for them. There was no doubt in your mind that your son was going to grow up to be just like his father.

When the song ended, the crowd cheered loudly for Wyld Stallyns and your son. Bill and Ted thanked everyone for coming out and told them goodnight before walking your way. Your son ran your way and jumped into your waiting arms.

“Did you see me, mommy?!” He yelled out excitedly as Ted took his headphones off of him. “That was most excellent!”

“I did see you,” you told him and kissed his cheek. “You were amazing, sweetie. Our very own little rockstar, but you know you’re not supposed to run out on stage like that.”

“I’m sorry, mommy,” he told you and put on those puppy dog eyes.

“It’s alright,” you told him. “Uncle Bill and daddy didn’t seem to mind.”

“No way,” Bill said with a grin. “Little dude is welcome to join us on stage anytime even though he totally stole the show from us. The crowd loved him.”

“Of course,” you said and giggled. “Who couldn’t love this cool little dude?”

Ted Jr. smiled before you put him down and you all walked back to the band’s shared dressing room. Bill and the others talked amongst themselves as they went to grab themselves some food. You, Ted, and Ted Jr. took a seat on the couch together.

“Your show was most excellent,” you told your husband with a smile.

“Thanks, babe,” he said with a smile before he drank some water.

“That was a triumphant show, daddy!” Ted jr. exclaimed from his spot between you and Ted. “Can I play with you and uncle Bill again?”

“Of course, little dude,” Ted told him and ruffled his hair. “You’re most welcome on stage with us any time.”

“Excellent!” Ted Jr. exclaimed then him and his father broke out in air guitar.

You giggled at the two of them and shook your head. They were basically twins. Ted Jr. jumped off of the couch to go tell his uncle Bill that he would be joining them again sometime.

“He really admires you,” you told Ted with a smile as you looked at him. “He’s your biggest fan.”

Ted smiled proudly as he glanced over at little Ted then he looked back at you. “You think so?”

“Ted, you’re his hero,” you told him, honestly. “He’s like your mini me. Remember how worried you were when I went into labor with him? You thought you wouldn’t be a good father. Look at you now, babe. You’re an excellent father and your son looks up to you so much.”

Ted grinned at that and leaned in to kiss you, sweetly before he wrapped you in a hug. “He looks up to you too, babe. He definitely doesn’t get his love of reading and drawing from me. That’s all you.”

“We’re doing a pretty good job, huh?” You asked as you both looked at Ted Jr., who was talking with his uncle Bill very animatedly.

“I’d say we’re doing a most excellent job, babe,” he replied.

Ted Jr. smiled before you put him down and you all walked back to the band’s shared dressing room. Bill and the others talked amongst themselves as they went to grab themselves some food. You, Ted, and Ted Jr. took a seat on the couch together.

“Your show was most excellent,” you told your husband with a smile.

“Thanks, babe,” he said with a smile before he drank some water.

“That was a triumphant show, daddy!” Ted jr. exclaimed from his spot between you and Ted. “Can I play with you and uncle Bill again?”

“Of course, little dude,” Ted told him and ruffled his hair. “You’re most welcome on stage with us any time.”

“Excellent!” Ted Jr. exclaimed then him and his father broke out in air guitar.

You giggled at the two of them and shook your head. They were basically twins. Ted Jr. jumped off of the couch to go tell his uncle Bill that he would be joining them again sometime.

“He really admires you,” you told Ted with a smile as you looked at him. “He’s your biggest fan.”

Ted smiled proudly as he glanced over at little Ted then he looked back at you. “You think so?”

“Ted, you’re his hero,” you told him, honestly. “He’s like your mini me. Remember how worried you were when I went into labor with him? You thought you wouldn’t be a good father. Look at you now, babe. You’re an excellent father and your son looks up to you so much.”

Ted grinned at that and leaned in to kiss you, sweetly before he wrapped you in a hug. “He looks up to you too, babe. He definitely doesn’t get his love of reading and drawing from me. That’s all you.”

“We’re doing a pretty good job, huh?” You asked as you both looked at Ted Jr., who was talking with his uncle Bill very animatedly.

“I’d say we’re doing a most excellent job, babe,” he replied.
